8/pans-labyrinth-2006-horned-monster-girl.jpg/96x54-cropped/pans-labyrinth-2006-horned-monster-girl.jpg","altText":null},"name":"Pan's Labyrinth","url":"/film/80a5c68c-6519-56a5-b38c-0d246f6e278b/pans-labyrinth","summary":{"text":"Guillermo del Toro creates an operatically beautiful fantasy world for a girl escaping the all too real brutalities of fascist Spain in 1944.","html":"\r\n\tGuillermo del Toro creates an operatically beautiful fantasy world for a girl escaping the all too real brutalities of fascist Spain in 1944.\r\n"},"fullDescription":"\r\n\t&ldquo;A film to return to, like a country waiting to be explored: a maze of dead ends and new life.&rdquo;\r\n\tAnthony Lane, The New Yorker, 2007\r\n\r\n\tSadism and savagery may rule the waking life of ten-year-old Ofelia (Ivana Baquero) &ndash; sent to live with her new stepfather, the brutal Captain Vidal (Sergi L&oacute;pez) &ndash; but a fairytale existence spawned by her reading gives her an alternate night-time existence as a princess set three tasks by a mysterious faun.\r\n\r\n\tThe tug-of-war between the ordinary and extraordinary is the rich theme at the heart of director Guillermo del Toro&rsquo;s other films, including Cronos (1993), The Devil&rsquo;s Backbone (2001) and his two Hellboy comic-book adaptations (2004 and 2008), but here it finds its ultimate expression as fantasy provides shelter from unspeakable reality.\r\n\r\n\tThe film won Oscars for cinematography, art direction and make-up, but controversially lost out as Best Foreign Language Film to Stefan Ruzowitsky&rsquo;s holocaust drama The Counterfeiters (2006).\r\n\r\n\tWith its story of a girl taking refuge in fantasy from the reality of unhappy families in Franco&rsquo;s Spain, Pan&rsquo;s Labyrinth recalls Victor Erice&rsquo;s classic The Spirit of the Beehive (1973).\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Guillermo del Toro","producer":"Berta Navarro, Alfonso Cuarón, Frida Torresblanco, Álvaro Augustín","writer":"Guillermo del Toro",