ed city of Vienna, its professional charm worn perilously thin, its once grand buildings now shabby and tottering. Anton Karas’s solo zither score vividly captures the wheedling, brittle mood of the defeated city.” <strong>Philip Kemp</strong></p>\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Carol Reed","producer":"Carol Reed","writer":"Graham Greene","featuring":"Carol Reed, Joseph Cotten, Joseph Cotten"},"year":"1949","nameAndYear":"The Third Man (1949)","links":{"player":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-the-third-man-1949-online","southbank":""},"player":{"url":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/subscription/film/watch-the-third-man-1949-online","cta":"https://player.bfi.org.uk/rent/10819","pillar":"rentals","price":3.5,"duration":0},"performances":[],"tags":["BFI Player","Shop"],"productionCountries":"United Kingdom","runningTime":104,"sightAndSound":{"results":[{"position":63,"tied":true,"category":"critics"},{"position":172,"tied":true,"category":"directors"}],"voters":null},"products":[{"sku":"5055201828484","name":"The Third Man (Blu-ray)","format":"Blu-Ray","url":"http://shop.bfi.org.uk/dvd-blu-ray/sight-and-sound-100-greatest-films-of-all-time/the-third-man-blu-ray.html","price":"13.99"}]},"comments":[{"type":"p","key":"The greatest British film of all time, and a masterclass in telling a story off-screen as well as on it. So often in cinema it's more thrilling to follow the bad guy, and while Graham Greene's script leaves you in no doubt as to who the villain of the piece is, Orson Welles' performance means you are as obsessed by Harry Lime as every character in the story. There's no greater example of this than Lime's introduction, lit by a lone window light and smiling as if knew the secrets of the world. ","ref":null,"props":{"children":"The greatest British film of all time, and a masterclass in telling a story off-screen as well as on it. So often in cinema it's more thrilling to follow the bad guy, and while Graham Greene's script leaves you i